definitions.definition: To put under the influence of a spell; to affect by a spell; to bewitch ; to fascinate ; to charm .

main_definition: To put under the influence of a spell; to affect by a spell; to bewitch ; to fascinate ; to charm .

definitions.definition: ( intransitive , transitive , sometimes with “out” ) To write or say the letters that form a word or part of a word. [from 16th c.]
examples: I find it difficult to spell because I'm dyslexic.

definitions.definition: ( transitive , obsolete ) To read (something) as though letter by letter; to peruse slowly or with effort. [from 14th c.]
( transitive ) Of letters: to compose (a word). [from 19th c.]
( transitive , figuratively , with “out” ) To clarify ; to explain in detail. [from 20th c.]
examples: Please spell it out for me.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To indicate that (some event) will occur; typically followed by a single-word noun . [from 19th c.]
( obsolete ) To speak , to declaim . [9th–16th c.]
( obsolete ) To tell; to relate; to teach.

definitions.definition: To rest (someone or something), to give someone or something a rest or break.
examples: They spelled the horses and rested in the shade of some trees near a brook.

definitions.definition: To rest from work for a time.

main_definition: ( transitive ) To work in place of (someone).
secondary_definitions: ( transitive ) To rest (someone or something), to give someone or something a rest or break.
( intransitive , colloquial ) To rest from work for a time.
